1
00:02:04,541 --> 00:02:06,458
[keyboard keys clacking]

2
00:02:06,541 --> 00:02:08,666
♪

3
00:02:17,458 --> 00:02:18,750
[sighs]

4
00:02:18,833 --> 00:02:21,541
[GEEK] Scariest thing
in the world. People.

5
00:02:21,625 --> 00:02:23,750
♪

6
00:02:30,458 --> 00:02:32,083
[knock on door]

7
00:02:37,833 --> 00:02:39,000
[door opens]

8
00:02:44,875 --> 00:02:46,583
[KEIGO]
There's no work for you here.

9
00:02:53,208 --> 00:02:54,750
[KIKYO]
What do we do now?

10
00:02:54,833 --> 00:02:58,000
Well, it looks like this is
home sweet home for a while.

11
00:02:58,083 --> 00:03:00,708
I guess this is
what we deserve.

12
00:03:02,291 --> 00:03:03,625
I had a thought.

13
00:03:03,708 --> 00:03:05,750
Maybe we should tell
the two of them the truth.

14
00:03:05,833 --> 00:03:08,250
[sighs]
I agree, we should.

15
00:03:08,333 --> 00:03:10,041
It's for the best.

16
00:03:13,500 --> 00:03:14,833
[TAKUYA]
You have to eat.

17
00:03:16,083 --> 00:03:18,458
I know you might not have
much of an appetite, but...

18
00:03:19,541 --> 00:03:22,083
Geek is giving my bike
a little check-up.

19
00:03:22,166 --> 00:03:24,625
It'll take some time
to get fixed.

20
00:03:24,708 --> 00:03:26,333
You should try
to rest till then.

21
00:03:27,458 --> 00:03:28,708
-[YUKI] Takuya.
-[TAKUYA] Hmm?

22
00:03:29,750 --> 00:03:31,083
I'm so sorry.

23
00:03:32,333 --> 00:03:34,083
No need to apologize.

24
00:03:34,166 --> 00:03:35,333
Just say thanks.

25
00:03:41,125 --> 00:03:42,000
[groans softly]

26
00:03:45,791 --> 00:03:48,833
Seriously, I can't believe
you made it out of there.

27
00:03:52,458 --> 00:03:53,958
Did you know
that would happen?

28
00:03:54,041 --> 00:03:55,250
No way.

29
00:03:55,333 --> 00:03:57,291
Believe me,
I'm as shocked as you are.

30
00:03:57,375 --> 00:03:58,333
[KOUTA sighs]

31
00:03:59,541 --> 00:04:00,958
[KOUTA]
In the moment,

32
00:04:01,041 --> 00:04:04,333
I just thought, "Oh, wow.

33
00:04:04,416 --> 00:04:06,125
So, this is the part
where I die."

34
00:04:07,333 --> 00:04:10,333
My vision went dark, but then...

35
00:04:10,416 --> 00:04:11,875
[footsteps approaching]

36
00:04:14,333 --> 00:04:17,083
[groaning weakly]

37
00:04:19,958 --> 00:04:21,083
[TAKUYA]
Impossible.

38
00:04:21,166 --> 00:04:23,791
There's no way
he'd save you or Yumiko.

39
00:04:23,875 --> 00:04:26,041
You went against the Agency.

40
00:04:26,125 --> 00:04:27,208
No, you're wrong.

41
00:04:27,291 --> 00:04:29,500
You're really misjudging
Mr. Kaibara.

42
00:04:29,583 --> 00:04:31,083
Is that right?

43
00:04:31,166 --> 00:04:33,583
Then why'd he stop
my investigation?

44
00:04:33,666 --> 00:04:35,625
If we'd just exposed
the academy,

45
00:04:35,708 --> 00:04:38,500
then we could've saved
all those children.

46
00:04:38,583 --> 00:04:39,666
But, no.

47
00:04:39,750 --> 00:04:41,833
He sided with the Agency.

48
00:04:41,916 --> 00:04:45,041
I understand
how you could see it that way.

49
00:04:45,125 --> 00:04:48,125
It's just, I dug deeper
into it after everything.

50
00:04:48,208 --> 00:04:49,166
[YUMIKO]
Kouta.

51
00:04:49,250 --> 00:04:50,958
Please let me tell him, okay?

52
00:04:51,041 --> 00:04:54,458
Truth is, we had no choice
at the time.

53
00:04:54,541 --> 00:04:57,875
Believe it or not,
Mr. Kaibara actually saved you.

54
00:04:57,958 --> 00:04:59,208
[gasps]

55
00:05:04,958 --> 00:05:07,375
He was under heavy threats
from the Agency.

56
00:05:07,458 --> 00:05:09,166
If he didn't comply,

57
00:05:09,250 --> 00:05:11,875
then they would've killed
everyone in the firm.

58
00:05:11,958 --> 00:05:13,708
The only reason
he went against his values

59
00:05:13,791 --> 00:05:15,708
in the first place
was to save our lives.

60
00:05:17,041 --> 00:05:19,625
You think you're frustrated?

61
00:05:19,708 --> 00:05:21,541
Imagine how he feels.

62
00:05:24,083 --> 00:05:25,125
[TAKUYA]
Shit.

63
00:05:27,458 --> 00:05:29,208
[KIKYO]
Here, for you.

64
00:05:29,291 --> 00:05:30,875
Some undies and other basics.

65
00:05:30,958 --> 00:05:34,375
That stuff isn't Takuya's forte.

66
00:05:34,458 --> 00:05:35,500
Thanks a lot.

67
00:05:38,875 --> 00:05:39,750
[sighs]

68
00:05:42,166 --> 00:05:44,166
Yuki, listen.

69
00:05:44,250 --> 00:05:46,916
I know it's probably cruel
for me to tell you this now,

70
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:49,333
but the Lost isn't over.

71
00:05:49,416 --> 00:05:50,500
[gasps]

72
00:05:50,583 --> 00:05:52,625
[YUKI]
What do you mean?

73
00:05:53,708 --> 00:05:57,833
[KIKYO] Quite simply, the Lost
is expanding as we speak.

74
00:05:57,916 --> 00:05:59,291
[keyboard keys clack]

75
00:05:59,375 --> 00:06:01,583
Considering the energy
used to trigger the event,

76
00:06:01,666 --> 00:06:04,125
it should have expanded
to about this size.

77
00:06:05,458 --> 00:06:07,041
That's unreal.

78
00:06:07,125 --> 00:06:08,750
[KIKYO]
Except it isn't.

79
00:06:08,833 --> 00:06:11,333
So the Lost will continue
to grow until completion,

80
00:06:11,416 --> 00:06:13,416
and I'm afraid
that's just a fact of life now.

81
00:06:13,500 --> 00:06:15,416
Of course it's a problem

82
00:06:15,500 --> 00:06:17,416
that the entire world
will need to face.

83
00:06:17,500 --> 00:06:21,041
The earliest danger
is decades from now.

84
00:06:21,125 --> 00:06:23,291
So at least we can be thankful
it isn't imminent.

85
00:06:25,041 --> 00:06:26,916
[TSUKI] If that hole
had properly connected,

86
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:29,500
then the Noah Project
would've been complete.

87
00:06:30,875 --> 00:06:33,375
You think this could
really be all Daichi's doing?

88
00:06:33,458 --> 00:06:34,666
[TAIYO]
It must be,

89
00:06:34,750 --> 00:06:36,583
that's the only thing
that makes sense.

90
00:06:36,666 --> 00:06:40,166
He's obviously using some method
to stop the expansion.

91
00:06:40,250 --> 00:06:43,916
[TSUKI] But I can't imagine
he's still alive in there.

92
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:46,291
[SUZUNA] We've tried to send
messages into Lost,

93
00:06:46,375 --> 00:06:47,916
always to no avail.

94
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:50,458
[TAIYO] But don't forget
that once there was a message

95
00:06:50,541 --> 00:06:52,750
that originated from Lost.

96
00:06:52,833 --> 00:06:54,208
And you think
it was from him?

97
00:06:54,291 --> 00:06:55,708
Yes.

98
00:06:55,791 --> 00:06:58,500
There's only one reason
Yuki would heading to Lost.

99
00:06:58,583 --> 00:07:01,666
She had to have received
a message from her father.

100
00:07:01,750 --> 00:07:04,083
Let Yuki run free
and have her awaken,

101
00:07:04,166 --> 00:07:06,625
or alternately,
have Souma go berserk.

102
00:07:06,708 --> 00:07:08,500
I was convinced
that either would be enough

103
00:07:08,583 --> 00:07:11,250
to substitute
for the portal device.

104
00:07:11,333 --> 00:07:13,833
But it was actually
simpler than I thought.

105
00:07:13,916 --> 00:07:16,291
As long as we eliminate Daichi,

106
00:07:16,375 --> 00:07:18,291
the portal will
reach completion.

107
00:07:21,083 --> 00:07:22,458
You okay?

108
00:07:22,541 --> 00:07:25,333
I know you said the danger
is still decades away,

109
00:07:25,416 --> 00:07:28,833
but the hole will eventually
swallow everything, right?

110
00:07:28,916 --> 00:07:32,041
I have to go
and do something about it.

111
00:07:32,125 --> 00:07:34,083
My father's calling for me.

112
00:07:34,166 --> 00:07:37,125
Even that message might've
been a trap set by the enemy.

113
00:07:37,208 --> 00:07:39,458
[YUKI] Are you saying
that should stop me from going?

114
00:07:39,541 --> 00:07:42,166
Because if there's even
the smallest chance,

115
00:07:42,250 --> 00:07:43,458
then I have to go.

116
00:07:43,541 --> 00:07:44,500
[gasps]

117
00:07:44,583 --> 00:07:47,125
Okay, then listen to me.

118
00:07:47,208 --> 00:07:50,583
I need to tell you about
the true dangers of Lost.

119
00:07:50,666 --> 00:07:52,833
-[TAKUYA] Dissolve the contract?
-[EIJI] Yeah.

120
00:07:52,916 --> 00:07:55,333
Even after everything
that's happened?

121
00:07:55,416 --> 00:07:58,708
I thought the objective
was to deliver Yuki to Lost.

122
00:07:58,791 --> 00:08:01,375
Well, there's something
I haven't actually told you.

123
00:08:02,458 --> 00:08:04,375
What do you mean,
we have to eliminate Daichi?

124
00:08:04,458 --> 00:08:06,375
How would we do that?

125
00:08:06,458 --> 00:08:09,125
[TAIYO] I've decided I'll be
heading to Lost myself.

126
00:08:09,208 --> 00:08:10,666
Are you serious?

127
00:08:10,750 --> 00:08:12,875
You know those surge particles
are dangerous.

128
00:08:12,958 --> 00:08:14,875
You can't honestly
be considering that.

129
00:08:14,958 --> 00:08:17,791
[TAIYO] All of our experiments
up until now have been conducted

130
00:08:17,875 --> 00:08:20,666
in order to become unaffected
by such a thing.

131
00:08:20,750 --> 00:08:23,083
[TSUKI]
But the medicine is incomplete.

132
00:08:23,166 --> 00:08:25,708
If a normal person
were to walk into Lost...

133
00:08:26,833 --> 00:08:28,458
[TAKUYA]
Okay, sure, I'll bite.

134
00:08:28,541 --> 00:08:30,125
What are surge particles?

135
00:08:30,208 --> 00:08:32,791
An unknown particle
that permeates all of Lost.

136
00:08:32,875 --> 00:08:34,125
It's not good news.

137
00:08:34,208 --> 00:08:35,708
It has devastating effects

138
00:08:35,791 --> 00:08:38,458
on the nervous systems
of living creatures.

139
00:08:38,541 --> 00:08:41,083
If you are exposed to it
for long periods of time,

140
00:08:41,166 --> 00:08:44,208
it erodes the hippocampus
and causes memory loss.

141
00:08:44,291 --> 00:08:46,125
At worst,
it can cause abnormalities

142
00:08:46,208 --> 00:08:47,541
in your mental state.

143
00:08:47,625 --> 00:08:50,208
-After that, you may die.
-[YUKI gasps]

144
00:08:50,291 --> 00:08:52,375
[KIKYO] I'm sure that's why
there have been no survivors

145
00:08:52,458 --> 00:08:54,041
from any of the survey teams.

146
00:08:54,125 --> 00:08:55,791
Not a single one.

147
00:08:57,625 --> 00:08:59,333
-So...
-[inhales sharply]

148
00:08:59,416 --> 00:09:01,291
[TAKUYA] You were sending
Yuki and me to Lost

149
00:09:01,375 --> 00:09:03,500
even though you already knew
all of that, right?

150
00:09:03,583 --> 00:09:04,458
Yeah.

151
00:09:05,458 --> 00:09:06,875
And I'm sorry,

152
00:09:06,958 --> 00:09:09,041
but we can't put the two of you
in any more danger.

153
00:09:09,125 --> 00:09:11,125
You may think
I'm a selfish prick

154
00:09:11,208 --> 00:09:13,208
but this is how I really feel.

155
00:09:13,291 --> 00:09:16,083
The director of Lacuna, Taiyo,
has started to move.

156
00:09:17,125 --> 00:09:18,041
Taiyo?

157
00:09:18,125 --> 00:09:19,750
That creepy guy?

158
00:09:20,958 --> 00:09:22,291
It seems he's trying
to communicate

159
00:09:22,375 --> 00:09:23,916
with something in Lost.

160
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:27,333
If Yuki moves, he'll eliminate
her without hesitation.

161
00:09:27,416 --> 00:09:29,000
He is a dangerous man.

162
00:09:29,083 --> 00:09:30,125
[groans softly]

163
00:09:30,208 --> 00:09:32,291
Please, I'm begging you.

164
00:09:32,375 --> 00:09:34,541
Don't go.

165
00:09:34,625 --> 00:09:36,041
[sighs]

166
00:09:43,375 --> 00:09:44,833
[rattling]

167
00:09:46,458 --> 00:09:47,875
[GEEK]
There! See what I mean?

168
00:09:47,958 --> 00:09:50,291
Yua's sweet moves just now.
Did you see that?

169
00:09:50,375 --> 00:09:51,666
-[music playing on laptop]
-No?

170
00:09:51,750 --> 00:09:53,875
[GEEK] Come on, you have
to pay attention.

171
00:09:53,958 --> 00:09:55,333
Right there. See?

172
00:09:55,416 --> 00:09:57,833
She fell one beat behind,
but Yua made it through

173
00:09:57,916 --> 00:10:00,416
with some ad-libbing
like the freakin' champ she is.

174
00:10:00,500 --> 00:10:01,333
Cool.

175
00:10:01,416 --> 00:10:02,833
Isn't that amazing?

176
00:10:02,916 --> 00:10:05,041
I mean, she gets some flack
for being devious,

177
00:10:05,125 --> 00:10:07,375
but she works harder
than anyone else, for sure.

178
00:10:07,458 --> 00:10:09,875
She really pays attention
to her surroundings, you know?

179
00:10:09,958 --> 00:10:10,916
I see, yeah.

180
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:12,416
Oh, if you're hungry,

181
00:10:12,500 --> 00:10:15,375
help yourself to some rice balls
and potato chips.

182
00:10:15,458 --> 00:10:18,416
[TAKUYA] Why do you always eat
those two things together?

183
00:10:18,500 --> 00:10:20,208
[GEEK]
Because it tastes like magic!

184
00:10:20,291 --> 00:10:21,291
Here, try this.

185
00:10:21,375 --> 00:10:22,333
Come on, open up.

186
00:10:23,541 --> 00:10:25,250
'Kay, now for
the rice ball chaser.

187
00:10:25,333 --> 00:10:27,666
Is this what you mean
by "together"?

188
00:10:27,750 --> 00:10:28,750
Just do it.

189
00:10:28,833 --> 00:10:30,125
There it is.

190
00:10:30,208 --> 00:10:32,250
Tell me your mouth
isn't in heaven right now.

191
00:10:32,333 --> 00:10:34,666
You can't,
because crunchy-juicy-tastic!

192
00:10:36,791 --> 00:10:38,458
Oh, time for Yua's solo.

193
00:10:38,541 --> 00:10:41,708
Listen to these lyrics,
they're so good, man.

194
00:10:41,791 --> 00:10:43,416
-[music playing on laptop]
-[GEEK humming]

195
00:10:47,291 --> 00:10:48,416
-[TAKUYA sighs]
-[GEEK] Hmm?

196
00:10:51,333 --> 00:10:52,500
-Hey. Wait.
-[brakes squeal]

197
00:10:54,125 --> 00:10:55,291
Hold on. Be right back.

198
00:11:01,041 --> 00:11:02,416
Thought you might
wanna borrow it.

199
00:11:02,500 --> 00:11:04,250
[TAKUYA] Didn't I just
watch that with you?

200
00:11:04,333 --> 00:11:06,875
[GEEK] Yeah, but it only
gets better with each viewing.

201
00:11:06,958 --> 00:11:08,083
[TAKUYA]
Hmm.

202
00:11:08,166 --> 00:11:09,666
[GEEK]
You have to return it, though.

203
00:11:09,750 --> 00:11:11,791
It's my one treasure.

204
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:17,875
[TAKUYA]
Sure.

205
00:11:23,083 --> 00:11:24,416
Look at that.

206
00:11:24,500 --> 00:11:25,708
What a great view.

207
00:11:31,208 --> 00:11:32,041
Yeah.

208
00:11:36,625 --> 00:11:38,375
[gasps]

209
00:11:38,458 --> 00:11:39,458
[sighs]

210
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:42,333
Yuki.

211
00:11:42,416 --> 00:11:43,875
What's the first thing
you wanna do

212
00:11:43,958 --> 00:11:46,375
when life goes back to normal?

213
00:11:46,458 --> 00:11:47,541
Huh?

214
00:11:47,625 --> 00:11:48,500
[TAKUYA]
Well?

215
00:11:50,375 --> 00:11:52,875
Normal life? What is that?

216
00:11:52,958 --> 00:11:54,500
I haven't even thought about it.

217
00:11:55,625 --> 00:11:57,333
Too many things have happened.

218
00:12:00,333 --> 00:12:02,708
Well, unfortunately,
the scooter's not ready yet.

219
00:12:02,791 --> 00:12:04,291
Think you can wait
a little bit longer?

220
00:12:05,791 --> 00:12:07,000
Oh, yeah.

221
00:12:07,083 --> 00:12:08,500
Of course.

222
00:12:09,541 --> 00:12:10,875
[door opens]

223
00:12:10,958 --> 00:12:12,083
-[YUKI sighs]
-[door closes]

224
00:12:12,875 --> 00:12:14,541
[GEEK]
What did you say?!

225
00:12:14,625 --> 00:12:17,750
So, Takuya was an experiment
for you from the beginning?!

226
00:12:17,833 --> 00:12:18,916
[KOUTA]
Would you calm down?

227
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:20,291
[GEEK]
If that's the case,

228
00:12:20,375 --> 00:12:22,125
then you guys are no different
from the Agency!

229
00:12:22,208 --> 00:12:23,500
-[YUMIKO] True.
-[KOUTA and GEEK] Huh?

230
00:12:23,583 --> 00:12:26,083
Pushing them forward,
holding them back.

231
00:12:26,166 --> 00:12:27,916
You're master manipulators.

232
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:29,375
Yeah, you're right.

233
00:12:29,458 --> 00:12:31,166
Jerking them
around like that.

234
00:12:31,250 --> 00:12:33,458
It only makes it more painful
for those two.

235
00:12:35,166 --> 00:12:36,875
♪

236
00:12:45,791 --> 00:12:47,458
[keyboard keys clacking]

237
00:12:47,541 --> 00:12:49,250
[machine powering on]

238
00:12:51,333 --> 00:12:53,583
As I thought,
this line is the limit.

239
00:13:02,083 --> 00:13:03,583
[TSUKI]
The ingredients are balanced

240
00:13:03,666 --> 00:13:05,125
for surge particle blocking.

241
00:13:05,208 --> 00:13:08,333
The theory checks out,
so this doesn't make sense.

242
00:13:08,416 --> 00:13:11,833
Which means that we must be
missing an essential factor.

243
00:13:11,916 --> 00:13:14,250
Prepare more test subjects.

244
00:13:14,333 --> 00:13:15,916
But, wait, if we do more...

245
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:17,916
[TAIYO]
As long as the portal connects,

246
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:19,958
the Agency will
no longer matter.

247
00:13:20,041 --> 00:13:22,625
-Hurry.
-Right.

248
00:13:22,708 --> 00:13:23,708
[TSUKI groans softly]

249
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:28,791
[indistinct chatter]

250
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:33,416
[SHOPKEEPER]
Now, didn't you see that story

251
00:13:33,500 --> 00:13:35,166
last night about cabbage?

252
00:13:35,250 --> 00:13:36,625
[WOMAN]
That it's good for the skin?

253
00:13:36,708 --> 00:13:39,208
Right. Not that you would
need anything like that.

254
00:13:39,291 --> 00:13:42,041
[WOMAN] Oh, you charmer.
I'll take one.

255
00:13:42,125 --> 00:13:43,208
[SHOPKEEPER]
Good choice.

256
00:13:43,291 --> 00:13:44,208
How do you think you did?

257
00:13:44,291 --> 00:13:46,125
Well, I know I bombed English.

258
00:13:46,208 --> 00:13:47,375
Yeah, same here.

259
00:13:47,458 --> 00:13:49,208
World history, math,
and Japanese, too.

260
00:13:49,291 --> 00:13:50,791
[STUDENT]
Oh, that sucks.

261
00:13:50,875 --> 00:13:53,416
[BOY] That's no fair,
I'm telling Mom!

262
00:13:53,500 --> 00:13:55,375
I want to learn piano, too.

263
00:13:55,458 --> 00:13:57,333
[GIRL] You don't have
a good ear, so you can't.

264
00:13:57,416 --> 00:13:58,916
Well, you're ugly, so you can't.

265
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:01,000
[GIRL]
Mom, did you hear him?

266
00:14:01,083 --> 00:14:02,958
He's being such a brat.

267
00:14:03,041 --> 00:14:05,333
Huh? Wait, Why me?

268
00:14:05,416 --> 00:14:06,916
Why do I have to do it?

269
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:09,083
If it's so important,
then you tell him yourself.

270
00:14:10,250 --> 00:14:11,625
Huh? Why tomatoes?

271
00:14:11,708 --> 00:14:12,791
[MAN]
Shh.

272
00:14:12,875 --> 00:14:14,500
Ugh! Wait, can you hear me now?

273
00:14:15,750 --> 00:14:18,458
Ugh! Jeez, this is so not fun.

274
00:14:18,541 --> 00:14:20,166
[cell phone rings]

275
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:23,166
[TAKUYA]
What's up?

276
00:14:23,250 --> 00:14:24,458
[KOUTA over phone]
Hey, what you doin'?

277
00:14:24,541 --> 00:14:25,958
You're free right now,
aren't you? Right?

278
00:14:26,041 --> 00:14:28,291
Would you mind picking up
some tomatoes?

279
00:14:28,375 --> 00:14:29,166
Huh?

280
00:14:29,250 --> 00:14:30,333
[KOUTA]
Yeah.

281
00:14:30,416 --> 00:14:31,916
Yumiko wants to make
some pescatora,

282
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:33,291
so she needs tomatoes.

283
00:14:33,375 --> 00:14:36,000
She says the right ingredients
are important.

284
00:14:36,083 --> 00:14:39,166
Wait, which tomato
did she ask for, again?

285
00:14:39,250 --> 00:14:40,958
Well, anyway,
apparently she has to have

286
00:14:41,041 --> 00:14:42,291
a certain type of tomato.

287
00:14:42,375 --> 00:14:44,291
[TAKUYA]
I've never seen her cook before.

288
00:14:44,375 --> 00:14:45,875
This is a first.

289
00:14:47,250 --> 00:14:48,958
[KOUTA] Cool, I'll text you
the place, okay?

290
00:14:49,041 --> 00:14:51,083
Thanks for taking care of that.

291
00:14:51,166 --> 00:14:52,041
[TAKUYA]
Hey.

292
00:14:53,625 --> 00:14:54,625
[sighs]

293
00:14:56,291 --> 00:14:57,625
What the hell, man?

294
00:15:00,708 --> 00:15:02,916
I've been thinking
about the lab lately.

295
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:04,875
About what it was like
back then.

296
00:15:04,958 --> 00:15:06,208
Those were the days.

297
00:15:06,291 --> 00:15:08,125
We were so proud
of being at the forefront

298
00:15:08,208 --> 00:15:10,583
of scientific research,
remember?

299
00:15:10,666 --> 00:15:11,791
It was fulfilling.

300
00:15:11,875 --> 00:15:13,416
Yeah for me, too.

301
00:15:13,500 --> 00:15:14,791
I mean, a scientist couldn't ask

302
00:15:14,875 --> 00:15:17,291
for a better situation
than that.

303
00:15:17,375 --> 00:15:20,708
After all, we got to work
alongside Daichi's genius.

304
00:15:20,791 --> 00:15:22,791
He was a pretty strange guy,

305
00:15:22,875 --> 00:15:25,166
but he sure loved his family.

306
00:15:25,250 --> 00:15:28,083
Every time he spoke,
it was about Yuki or Souma.

307
00:15:28,166 --> 00:15:30,125
Hmm. That's called
a doting parent.

308
00:15:30,208 --> 00:15:31,041
[KIKYO chuckles]

309
00:15:33,666 --> 00:15:35,000
[EIJI]
Just...

310
00:15:35,083 --> 00:15:36,666
Sometimes I find
myself wondering

311
00:15:36,750 --> 00:15:39,583
what Daichi really thought
of his own research.

312
00:15:39,666 --> 00:15:42,750
Remember, science can be
poison or medicine

313
00:15:42,833 --> 00:15:44,541
depending on how it's used.

314
00:15:44,625 --> 00:15:47,875
[EIJI] We are partially
responsible for the Lost,

315
00:15:47,958 --> 00:15:49,333
and that's just a fact.

316
00:15:49,416 --> 00:15:51,791
We have to face
that responsibility, now.

317
00:15:51,875 --> 00:15:53,250
[KIKYO grunts softly]

318
00:15:53,333 --> 00:15:56,041
Easy enough to say,
but will you follow through?

319
00:15:56,125 --> 00:15:58,000
Yeah.

320
00:15:58,083 --> 00:16:01,666
I wanna put being human before
being a scientist for once.

321
00:16:01,750 --> 00:16:03,416
So no matter what happens,

322
00:16:03,500 --> 00:16:05,666
it's our duty to
fully support their decision.

323
00:16:05,750 --> 00:16:07,541
That's the least we can do.

324
00:16:07,625 --> 00:16:08,958
[chuckles softly]
Hmm.

325
00:16:20,208 --> 00:16:22,416
[YUMIKO] You haven't had a treat
for a while, huh?

326
00:16:23,541 --> 00:16:25,375
An occasional break is healthy.

327
00:16:28,583 --> 00:16:29,458
[YUKI scoffs]

328
00:16:36,500 --> 00:16:37,333
[sighs]

329
00:16:44,041 --> 00:16:46,333
Hey. Want some tomatoes?

330
00:16:47,750 --> 00:16:50,458
♪

331
00:16:50,541 --> 00:16:53,041
So, is that enough water?

332
00:16:53,125 --> 00:16:54,583
Wouldn't think so, right?

333
00:16:54,666 --> 00:16:57,166
At first I watered them
a ridiculous amount.

334
00:16:57,250 --> 00:16:59,333
But they didn't end up
tasting great.

335
00:17:00,791 --> 00:17:02,375
Unfortunately, what I'd done

336
00:17:02,458 --> 00:17:04,750
was zap those
tomatoes' will to live.

337
00:17:04,833 --> 00:17:08,041
This is just the right amount
to grow them hardy.

338
00:17:08,125 --> 00:17:09,791
[twig snaps]

339
00:17:09,875 --> 00:17:11,166
Here, try one.

340
00:17:15,250 --> 00:17:18,625
Takuya knew
about surge particles.

341
00:17:18,708 --> 00:17:20,833
That's what
you're telling me, right?

342
00:17:20,916 --> 00:17:22,416
[YUMIKO]
Yes.

343
00:17:22,500 --> 00:17:23,958
Yeah, that's what I thought.

344
00:17:27,833 --> 00:17:29,291
[YUMIKO]
You've decided, haven't you?

345
00:17:29,375 --> 00:17:31,750
[YUKI gasps, sighs]

346
00:17:31,833 --> 00:17:33,875
I say we order another.

347
00:17:33,958 --> 00:17:35,000
Huh?

348
00:17:35,083 --> 00:17:36,916
Just one, we'll split.
[chuckles]

349
00:17:38,583 --> 00:17:39,916
[YUKI chuckles softly]
Hmm.

350
00:17:42,333 --> 00:17:43,791
You've got plenty there.

351
00:17:43,875 --> 00:17:46,500
She'll be able to make it
even if she messes up.

352
00:17:46,583 --> 00:17:48,750
I appreciate this.

353
00:17:48,833 --> 00:17:50,375
[engine revving]

354
00:17:50,458 --> 00:17:51,291
[KAIBARA]
Takuya.

355
00:17:52,416 --> 00:17:54,125
It's your life, you know.

356
00:17:54,208 --> 00:17:55,875
Go live it however you want.

357
00:17:58,416 --> 00:17:59,833
[motor scooter engine revving]

358
00:18:10,250 --> 00:18:11,083
[TSUKI groans softly]

359
00:18:14,666 --> 00:18:17,208
[TSUKI]
We have to stop this, Taiyo.

360
00:18:17,291 --> 00:18:19,958
[TAIYO] No. We're sure
of the balance of ingredients

361
00:18:20,041 --> 00:18:21,541
for the inhibitor drug.

362
00:18:21,625 --> 00:18:23,708
We just need the missing piece.

363
00:18:23,791 --> 00:18:27,416
Something from
a parallel universe, not here.

364
00:18:27,500 --> 00:18:28,958
Since we're from there,
originally,

365
00:18:29,041 --> 00:18:30,750
does that mean
we should be able to enter again

366
00:18:30,833 --> 00:18:32,625
without losing
any of our memories?

367
00:18:32,708 --> 00:18:34,458
We don't have enough
evidence to support that.

368
00:18:34,541 --> 00:18:36,875
Daichi retained his memories
once inside Lost,

369
00:18:36,958 --> 00:18:38,791
that's one piece of proof.

370
00:18:38,875 --> 00:18:41,500
If only we can get
that hypothesis confirmed.

371
00:18:43,666 --> 00:18:44,500
I'll do it.

372
00:18:44,583 --> 00:18:47,333
I'll be the test subject.

373
00:18:47,416 --> 00:18:48,250
[TAIYO]
Huh?

374
00:18:49,666 --> 00:18:50,875
You're sure?

375
00:18:52,916 --> 00:18:54,708
It'll be fine.

376
00:18:54,791 --> 00:18:57,500
I know there's no way
that I could ever forget you.

377
00:18:58,791 --> 00:18:59,708
Tsuki.

378
00:19:03,375 --> 00:19:04,916
Go ahead.

379
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:06,833
-[keyboard keys clacking]
-[whirring]

380
00:19:08,875 --> 00:19:10,250
♪

381
00:19:14,416 --> 00:19:16,625
-[keyboard keys clacking]
-[whirring]

382
00:19:20,541 --> 00:19:21,375
[beeps]

383
00:19:22,666 --> 00:19:23,625
Huh?

384
00:19:25,166 --> 00:19:26,666
Taiyo?

385
00:19:26,750 --> 00:19:28,958
[gasps] You see?
It's true.

386
00:19:29,041 --> 00:19:31,375
I knew I would remember
you perfectly.

387
00:19:31,458 --> 00:19:33,375
[TAIYO]
Very encouraging results.

388
00:19:33,458 --> 00:19:35,208
However, just in case,

389
00:19:35,291 --> 00:19:37,208
what do you say
we test the upper limits?

390
00:19:37,291 --> 00:19:39,041
[gasps]

391
00:19:39,125 --> 00:19:40,958
Wait, what? Why?

392
00:19:41,041 --> 00:19:43,375
[steady beeping]

393
00:19:43,458 --> 00:19:45,875
Let me out of here! Please!

394
00:19:45,958 --> 00:19:48,208
Why are you doing this to me?
Taiyo!

395
00:19:53,625 --> 00:19:55,875
The hypothesis
has been confirmed.

396
00:20:00,083 --> 00:20:00,916
[rustles]

397
00:20:02,583 --> 00:20:04,000
How is the bike?

398
00:20:04,083 --> 00:20:06,041
Well, it's all fixed up.

399
00:20:06,125 --> 00:20:07,416
Oh.

400
00:20:12,666 --> 00:20:14,791
-Hey.
-[TAKUYA] Hmm?

401
00:20:14,875 --> 00:20:17,375
[YUKI] What's your idea of
a normal life, Takuya?

402
00:20:18,416 --> 00:20:21,333
[TAKUYA] Having a place to stay,
a place to work,

403
00:20:21,416 --> 00:20:22,708
and some friends to be with.

404
00:20:24,416 --> 00:20:26,416
[YUKI]
That sounds nice.

405
00:20:26,500 --> 00:20:28,875
[TAKUYA] Normal is the best kind
of happiness.

406
00:20:28,958 --> 00:20:31,625
I agree, it sounds great.

407
00:20:32,666 --> 00:20:33,833
Once everything is over,

408
00:20:33,916 --> 00:20:35,791
I hope I'll be able
to have that.

409
00:20:38,166 --> 00:20:41,083
I wonder
what's the best place to live.

410
00:20:41,166 --> 00:20:42,458
I'd like a place
with a cool view.

411
00:20:43,541 --> 00:20:45,458
A house beside the sea.

412
00:20:45,541 --> 00:20:47,291
I think I'd like a cat, too.

413
00:20:47,375 --> 00:20:48,958
[TAKUYA]
A big window would be good.

414
00:20:49,041 --> 00:20:50,250
The cat would love it.

415
00:20:50,333 --> 00:20:53,041
Wonder what color
the curtains should be.

416
00:20:53,125 --> 00:20:54,375
Blue's nice.

417
00:20:54,458 --> 00:20:55,708
[YUKI]
What?

418
00:20:55,791 --> 00:20:58,291
Come on, a blue sea
behind blue curtains?

419
00:20:58,375 --> 00:20:59,583
[TAKUYA]
Oh, good point.

420
00:20:59,666 --> 00:21:01,208
Green, then.

421
00:21:01,291 --> 00:21:02,166
[YUKI]
Yeah.

422
00:21:02,250 --> 00:21:03,458
I like the sound of that.

423
00:21:03,541 --> 00:21:06,333
And I guess the furniture
should match.

424
00:21:06,416 --> 00:21:09,083
[TAKUYA] I'll come visit
from time to time.

425
00:21:09,166 --> 00:21:11,666
[YUKI]
Yes, and I'll make dinner.

426
00:21:11,750 --> 00:21:13,833
[TAKUYA] Nothing fancy,
just coffee and toast.

427
00:21:13,916 --> 00:21:16,291
[YUKI] No way,
what're you talking about?

428
00:21:16,375 --> 00:21:18,375
It has to be white rice
and miso soup.

429
00:21:18,458 --> 00:21:20,083
[TAKUYA]
Ah, a traditionalist.

430
00:21:21,166 --> 00:21:24,083
[YUKI] It must be wonderful,
living a normal life.

431
00:21:24,166 --> 00:21:25,291
[TAKUYA]
Yeah.

432
00:21:25,375 --> 00:21:27,166
[YUKI]
I'm determined not to forget.

433
00:21:27,250 --> 00:21:28,333
[TAKUYA]
Same.

434
00:21:28,416 --> 00:21:30,375
No matter what happens
after this,

435
00:21:30,458 --> 00:21:33,125
let's try to remember,
that's where we're headed.

436
00:21:35,458 --> 00:21:37,458
♪

437
00:21:39,291 --> 00:21:40,625
[YUKI]
Delicious.

438
00:21:40,708 --> 00:21:41,708
[TAKUYA]
Right?

439
00:21:45,333 --> 00:21:46,791
[motor scooter engine revving]

440
00:21:50,916 --> 00:21:51,750
[footsteps approaching]

441
00:21:56,625 --> 00:21:58,583
Hang on tight back there, okay?

442
00:21:58,666 --> 00:21:59,500
Yeah.

443
00:21:59,583 --> 00:22:00,541
[TAKUYA]
Let's go.

444
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:40,208
♪

445
00:23:43,666 --> 00:23:46,000
[YUKI]
Next episode, "Trust."

